            <div type="glosses">
                <note xml:id="STARSGLOSS" resp="#DCH"><p><hi rend="bold">&#x201C;<persName type="fictional" corresp="#HARRY">Harry</persName> took one of his
                    lesson books and made <persName type="fictional" corresp="#LUCY">Lucy</persName> learn the following constellations
                    with the number of stars&#x201D; (<title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSIIIA">MS IIIA</title>)&#x2014;</hi>In 
                    <!-- title and biblio --><ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#EDGEWORTHFRANKSEQUEL"><title type="lesson" corresp="#EDGEWORTHFRANKSEQUEL"><hi rend="italic">Frank: A Sequel to Frank in Early Lessons</hi></title></ref> 
                    by <persName corresp="#ME">Maria Edgeworth</persName>, <persName type="fictional" corresp="#FRANKME">Frank</persName> &#x201C;began counting to [his cousin] <persName type="fictional" corresp="#MARYME">Mary</persName> all the stars, 
                    whose names he had lately learned&#x201D;. In <persName type="fictional" corresp="#FRANKME">Frank</persName>&#x02BC;s case, he brings shame on himself for showing off, 
                    &#x201C;talking of . . . [the stars] as if they were all his own familiar acquaintance, 
                    and had scarcely been heard of by any body else in the world&#x201D;. While an episode like this in <persName corresp="#ME">Edgeworth</persName>&#x02BC;s 
                    <!-- series title --><title type="series" corresp="#EDGEWORTHEARLYLESSONS"><hi rend="italic">Early Lessons</hi></title> series may in part be behind the &#x201C;lesson book&#x201D; 
                    that <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>&#x02BC;s <persName type="fictional" corresp="#HARRY">Harry</persName> invokes to assign <persName type="fictional" corresp="#LUCY">Lucy</persName> her task, 
                    these tales do not contain data of the kind that <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName> sourced to compile lists of constellation names 
                    and corresponding numbers in his <title type="lesson" corresp="#JRHARRYANDLUCYVOL3">third volume of &#x201C;Harry and Lucy Concluded&#x201D;</title>. 
                    See <ref type="note" subtype="contextual" target="astronomy_note.php#PRINTSOURCES">Astronomical Education: Print Sources of Astronomical Education.</ref></p></note>
                
                <note xml:id="WATERGLOSS" resp="#DCH">Without reproducing <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>&#x02BC;s
                    diagram, one can see what he means by his treatment of water in his <date when="1930">1830</date> map of
                    <placeName corresp="#ENGLAND">England</placeName> and <placeName corresp="#WALES">Wales</placeName> (RFL, pl. xxv), in which the water is represented by thin
                    parallel horizontal lines, into which extend the names of coastal towns.</note>
                <!--The pointer to this gloss would be <ref type="gloss_contextual" target="filename_glosses.php#SOMETHINGUNIQUEGLOSS"/>.-->

                <note xml:id="DONQUIXOTEGLOSS" resp="#DCH"><title type="book" corresp="#CERVANTESDONQUIXOTE">Don quixote</title> [<persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>&#x02BC;s
                    note].</note>
                <!--The pointer to this gloss would be <ref type="gloss_contextual" target="filename_glosses.php#ALSOSOMETHINGUNIQUEGLOSS"/>.-->

                <note xml:id="TOOLATEGLOSS" resp="#DCH">For too read rather [<persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>&#x02BC;s note from the page
                    of &#x201C;ERRATA&#x201D;; see part 2, <title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSIIIA">MS IIIA</title>,
                    &#x201C;Description&#x201D;].</note>

                <note xml:id="EXTANTDRAFTGLOSS" resp="#DCH">Here begins the extant draft in <title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSII">MS II</title>.</note>

                <note xml:id="GEORGEIIIGLOSS" resp="#DCH">An error for <persName corresp="#KG2">George II</persName>. <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName> got it right in draft;
                    see textual note for this passage.</note>

                <note xml:id="DOUBLEPRINTGLOSS" resp="#DCH"><persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>&#x02BC;s example shows the printed letter m with
                    doubled downward strokes for &#x201C;double print,&#x201D; as opposed to the
                    usual single downward strokes for &#x201C;single letter.&#x201D;</note>

                <note xml:id="HARRYTHOUGHTGLOSS" resp="#DCH">&#x201C;<persName type="fictional" corresp="#HARRY">Harry</persName> thought&#x201D;&#x2014;<title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSII">MS II</title> reading; <title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSIIIA">MS IIIA</title>
                    copytext confused here, &#x201C;<persName type="fictional" corresp="#HARRY">Harrys</persName> thoundthat.&#x201D;</note>

                <note xml:id="MSIIIAGLOSS" resp="#DCH">Here ends the <title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSIIIA">MS IIIA</title> text; the remainder of the
                    copytext is taken from the <title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSII">MS II</title> draft, itself incomplete. In <title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSII">MS II</title>, the phrase
                    &#x201C;The figures&#x201D; does not follow the specifications for constructing
                    the theater; rather, first there occurs the one&#x2010;sentence paragraph about the
                    macaw (incomplete?), and then occurs &#x201C;The figures. . . .&#x201D; Some
                    confusion between draft and fair copy at this point might have contributed to
                    <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>&#x02BC;s discouragement with the project.</note>
            </div>
